<leg:heading><desig searchtype="DIV-NUM"><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT28.D3" type="ext"/>DIVISION 3</designum></desig><title searchtype="DIV-TITLE"> CONSOLIDATION ETC OF PROCEEDINGS [r 28.5]</title></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 28.5] r 28.5 Consolidation etc of proceedings (cf SCR Part 31, rule 7; DCR Part 12, rule 7) ">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5" type="ext"/>[r 28.5]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Consolidation etc of proceedings (cf SCR Part 31, rule 7; DCR Part 12, rule 7) </title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>28.5</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>If several proceedings are pending in the court and it appears to the court:</text></p>
<l><li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5.A"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5.A" type="ext"/>(a)</lilabel>
<p><text>that they involve a common question, or</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5.B"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5.B" type="ext"/>(b)</lilabel>
<p><text>that the rights to relief claimed in them are in respect of, or arise out of, the same transaction or series of transactions, or</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5.C"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R28-5.C" type="ext"/>(c)</lilabel>
<p><text>that for some other reason it is desirable to make an order under this rule,</text></p>
</li>
</l>
<p><text> the court may order those proceedings to be consolidated, or to be tried at the same time or one immediately after another, or may order any of them to be stayed until after the determination of any other of them.</text></p>
<glp:note>
<heading><title>Note:</title></heading>
<p>
<text>See also Division 5 of Part 6 with respect to joinder of causes of action and joinder of parties.</text></p></glp:note>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTES"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT28.R5.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTES</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.28-5-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[28.5.5] Consolidation"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.28-5-5" type="ext"/>[28.5.5] </edpnum><title>Consolidation</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Historically, formal consolidation was available at the instance of defendants sued in multiple proceedings by a common plaintiff: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007191" spanref="cr007191-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="VLR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1948"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="245"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Cameron v McBain</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007191-001" status="unval">[1948] VLR 245</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="49223" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Where multiple plaintiffs had commenced separate proceedings, the &#x201c;test case&#x201d; procedure was available: see 
<remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.28-5-20" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">[28.5.20]</remotelink>
.
In <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007192" spanref="cr007192-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QB"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1897"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="429"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Martin v Martin</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007192-001" status="unval">[1897] 1 QB 429</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> the Rules were held to permit consolidation on a plaintiff&#x2019;s application, though only where the proceedings raised did not raise discrete issues: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1908"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr007193" spanref="cr007193-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="LT"/><ci:volume num="100"/><ci:page num="61"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Lee v Arthur</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007193-001" status="unval">(1908) 100 LT 61</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="230322" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>.
However, the widely stated discretion under the present rule is inconsistent with inflexible limitations on the exercise of the power to order consolidation. As r 28.5(a) and (b) combine to make clear, there is no specific principle requiring, consolidation, nor any specific limitation against ordering it: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007194" spanref="cr007194-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200306316"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">A Goninan &amp; Co Ltd v Atlas Steels (Aust) Pty Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2003] NSWSC 956; <ci:span spanid="cr007194-001"> BC200306316</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="370658" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> explaining observations in <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007195" spanref="cr007195-001"><ci:reporter value="VR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1984"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="97"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr007195" spanref="cr007195-002"><ci:pinpoint num="100" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Bolwell Fibreglass Pty Ltd v Foley</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007195-001">[1984] VR 97</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr007195-002">at 100</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="10257" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Obviously, consolidation is most appropriate where the different claims and parties could have been joined in the one statement of claim: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Cameron v McBain</emph>
</citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>, above; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1929"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr007196" spanref="cr007196-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNEng"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1929"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="38[ndash ]39"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr007197" spanref="cr007197-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="TLR"/><ci:volume num="45"/><ci:page num="237"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Horwood v British Statesman Publishing Co Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007196-001" status="unval">[1929] WN 38</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr007197-002" status="unval">(1929) 45 TLR 237</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="135596" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007198" spanref="cr007198-001"><ci:reporter value="VR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1969"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="169"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Todd v Jones</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007198-001">[1969] VR 169</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="101266" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Bolwell Fibreglass Pty Ltd v Foley</emph>
</citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>, above, <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007199" spanref="cr007199-000"><ci:reporter value="VR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1984"/></ci:edition><ci:pinpoint num="100" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"><ci:span spanid="cr007199-000">at 100</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>.
The aptness of consolidation in such circumstances may be interpreted as implying its inappropriateness where those conditions are not met. But, the breadth of the power conferred by r 28.5(c), in particular, means that the hypothetically permissible joinder of all claims is just a consideration for, and not a requirement of, an order for consolidation. Consequently, if any of the conditions in r 28.5(a), (b) or (c) are met, proceedings may be consolidated despite the fact that they have completely different parties: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Horwood v British Statesman Publishing Co Ltd</emph>
</citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>, above. The conditions for the making of an order for consolidation imply that the principal purpose of such an order is to minimise cost and delay in the determination of the proceedings. That conclusion is reinforced by s 56 of the CPA: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">A Goninan &amp; Co Ltd v Atlas Steels (Aust) Pty Ltd</emph>
</citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>, above.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.28-5-10" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[28.5.10] Consolidation on terms"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.28-5-10" type="ext"/>[28.5.10] </edpnum><title>Consolidation on terms</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Consolidation may be ordered on terms. The terms imposed may involve the amendment or restyling of pleadings so far as is necessary to make consolidation effective and permit the efficient determination of the issues between the various parties: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007200" spanref="cr007200-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200306316"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">A Goninan &amp; Co Ltd v Atlas Steels (Aust) Pty Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2003] NSWSC 956; <ci:span spanid="cr007200-001"> BC200306316</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="370658" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.28-5-15" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[28.5.15] Prejudice as a reason to refuse consolidation"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.28-5-15" type="ext"/>[28.5.15] </edpnum><title>Prejudice as a reason to refuse consolidation</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>An order for consolidation may have potential to prejudice one or other of the parties. That prejudice may consist of the loss of a legitimate forensic advantage: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007201" spanref="cr007201-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200306316"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr007201" spanref="cr007201-002"><ci:pinpoint num="59" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">A Goninan &amp; Co Ltd v Atlas Steels (Aust) Pty Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2003] NSWSC 956; <ci:span spanid="cr007201-001"> BC200306316</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr007201-002">at [59]</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="370658" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; possible joinder of plaintiffs (requiring them to employ the same solicitor and counsel (see 
<remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.7-25-5" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">[7.25.5]</remotelink>
), or agree on settlement terms or avoid any conflicts of interest). Potential prejudice to one or other of the parties may provide a sufficient basis to refuse an order for consolidation: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1992"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr007202" spanref="cr007202-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="FLR"/><ci:volume num="108"/><ci:page num="140"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Fong Consultants Pty Ltd v Ati Management Pty Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007202-001" status="unval">(1992) 108 FLR 140</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="61544" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (availability of a limitation defence). In an appropriate case, a deconsolidating order can be made: see <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007203" spanref="cr007203-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="QB"/><ci:volume num="2"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1964"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="601"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr007204" spanref="cr007204-002"><ci:reporter value="All ER"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1964"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="705"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Lewis v Daily Telegraph Ltd (No 2)</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007203-001" status="unval">[1964] 2 QB 601</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr007204-002">[1964] 1 All ER 705</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="78946" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> and <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007205" spanref="cr007205-001"><ci:reporter value="VR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1984"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="97"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr007205" spanref="cr007205-002"><ci:pinpoint num="119" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Bolwell Fibreglass Pty Ltd v Foley</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007205-001">[1984] VR 97</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr007205-002">at 119</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="10257" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007206" spanref="cr007206-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC201109237"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Strata Plan 61287 v Brookfield Multiplex Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2011] NSWSC 1302; <ci:span spanid="cr007206-001"> BC201109237</ci:span> at [5]&#x2013;[14]</citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="542139" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (dispute about legal representation between commercial and residential strata corporation plaintiffs in consolidated proceedings).</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.28-5-20" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[28.5.20] Alternatives to formal consolidation"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.28-5-20" type="ext"/>[28.5.20] </edpnum><title>Alternatives to formal consolidation</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>An alternative to consolidation is the agreement by the parties or the order of the court that one of a series of proceedings be run as a test case. Care must be taken that a representative case is selected as the test case and the other proceedings are stayed, and there is an undertaking by those involved in the proceedings being stayed that they will abide by the result of the test case, see, for example, <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1878"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr007207" spanref="cr007207-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ChD"/><ci:volume num="9"/><ci:page num="459"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Amos v Chadwick</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007207-001" status="unval">(1878) 9 Ch D 459</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007208" spanref="cr007208-001"><ci:reporter value="All ER"/><ci:volume num="3"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1938"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="670"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Perry v Croydon Borough Council</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007208-001">[1938]
3 All ER 670</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>. The court may also make orders for separate trials of one or more of the claims in which numerous parties have been joined: see r 6.23. Separate trials may be an appropriate alternative to the power to order the determination of separate questions: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="2003"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr007209" spanref="cr007209-001"><ci:reporter value="ACSR"/><ci:volume num="45"/><ci:page num="298"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr007210" spanref="cr007210-002"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200302121"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr007210" spanref="cr007210-003"><ci:pinpoint num="8" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr007210" spanref="cr007210-004"><ci:pinpoint num="21" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr007210" spanref="cr007210-005"><ci:pinpoint num="23" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Dean-Willcocks v Cmr of Taxation</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007209-001">(2003) 45 ACSR 298</ci:span>; [2003] NSWSC 355; <ci:span spanid="cr007210-002"> BC200302121</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr007210-003">at [8],</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr007210-004">[21],</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr007210-005">[23]</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="362392" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> per Austin J. </text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.28-5-25" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[28.5.25] Representation"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.28-5-25" type="ext"/>[28.5.25] </edpnum><title>Representation</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>A consequence of a consolidation order is that the plaintiffs must act by the same solicitor (see r 7.25). The order for consolidation should preferably address costs prior to and subsequent to consolidation, and which party will have the conduct of the consolidated action. </text></p>
</bodytext>
